## Why this pattern

| Without custom errors                              | With custom errors                                           |
| -------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------ |
| `throw new Error("Email exists")`                  | `throw new EmailExistError()`                                |
| Catch with `if (err.message === "...")` (fragile)  | Catch with `if (err instanceof EmailExistError)` (type-safe) |
| Manual HTTP status code mapping in each controller | Auto-mapped via `err.statusCode`                             |
| Hardcoded message (no i18n)                        | i18n key auto-translated                                     |
| Error.stack leaked to client                       | errorHandler hides stack in production                       |

## Rules

1. **ALWAYS** extend `AppError` (or its children) — never throw raw `Error` in services
2. Message = **i18n key** (e.g. `"product.not_found"`) — NOT hardcoded text
3. `instanceof` check in errorHandler (rule 09) — KHÔNG dùng error.name string compare
4. Login error: ALWAYS same `AuthError` regardless of "email not found" or "wrong password" (security — no user enumeration)
5. Programming errors (e.g. unreachable code) → `InternalError` + Sentry capture
6. External API failures → `ExternalServiceError` with `service` tag for Sentry
7. New error class → add to `errors.ts` + check `errorHandler.ts` instanceof chain
